---
// Static SVG: Convex (converging) vs concave (diverging) lens ray diagrams.
// Ported verbatim from Bootcamp-test/public/ed/gcse-physics.html
---

<figure class="diagram">
  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="100%" viewBox="0 50 800 320" aria-label="Side-by-side diagram of convex and concave lens ray paths" role="img">

    <!-- ===== LEFT: Convex (converging) lens ===== -->
    <!-- Lens shape: fatter in the middle -->
    <path d="M200,100 C215,200 215,200 200,300 L190,300 C175,200 175,200 190,100 Z" fill="#5577ff" opacity="0.45" />
    <text x="160" y="330" font-size="14" fill="black" font-family="Arial" text-anchor="middle">Convex lens</text>
    <text x="160" y="348" font-size="12" fill="#555" font-family="Arial" text-anchor="middle">(converging)</text>

    <!-- Parallel incoming rays -->
    <line x1="60" y1="150" x2="195" y2="150" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="60" y1="175" x2="195" y2="175" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="60" y1="200" x2="195" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="60" y1="225" x2="195" y2="225" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="60" y1="250" x2="195" y2="250" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>

    <!-- Converging rays meeting at focal point -->
    <line x1="195" y1="150" x2="310" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="195" y1="175" x2="310" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="195" y1="200" x2="310" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="195" y1="225" x2="310" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="195" y1="250" x2="310" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>

    <!-- Focal point -->
    <circle cx="310" cy="200" r="5" fill="red" />
    <text x="318" y="196" font-family="Arial" font-size="13" fill="red">F</text>

    <!-- ===== RIGHT: Concave (diverging) lens ===== -->
    <!-- Lens shape: thinner in the middle -->
    <path d="M570,100 C555,200 555,200 570,300 L580,300 C595,200 595,200 580,100 Z" fill="#5577ff" opacity="0.45" />
    <text x="575" y="330" font-size="14" fill="black" font-family="Arial" text-anchor="middle">Concave lens</text>
    <text x="575" y="348" font-size="12" fill="#555" font-family="Arial" text-anchor="middle">(diverging)</text>

    <!-- Parallel incoming rays -->
    <line x1="450" y1="150" x2="570" y2="150" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="450" y1="175" x2="570" y2="175" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="450" y1="200" x2="570" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="450" y1="225" x2="570" y2="225" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="450" y1="250" x2="570" y2="250" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>

    <!-- Diverging rays spreading out -->
    <line x1="570" y1="150" x2="690" y2="110" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="570" y1="175" x2="690" y2="155" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="570" y1="200" x2="690" y2="200" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="570" y1="225" x2="690" y2="245" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
    <line x1="570" y1="250" x2="690" y2="290" stroke="orange" stroke-width="2"/>
  </svg>
  <figcaption>A convex lens bends light rays so they converge (meet) at the focal point. A concave lens bends them so they diverge (spread apart).</figcaption>
</figure>

<style>
  .diagram {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .diagram svg {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background: var(--color-bg-alt);
    padding: 1rem;
  }

  .diagram figcaption {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
</style>
